            ">The flop of MoviePass</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
          MoviePass, a startup with a seemingly brilliant idea of limitless movie-going for a flat monthly fee, collapsed under the weight of its own business model. Initially priced at $50/month, it later dropped to a widely publicized $10/month, which became <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-26-07-2025-their-biggest-mistake" target="_blank">their biggest mistake</a>.</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/moviepass-shutdown-announcement-email-2019.jpg" alt="In 2019, an email blast informed subscribers that MoviePass would cease operations imminently" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i> In 2019, an email blast informed subscribers that MoviePass would cease operations imminently. Credits: Darron Cummings/AP</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
          They created the service based on the gym membership model, also known as the breakage model. MoviePass believed that users wouldn’t use their membership regularly, but in reality, subscribers were seeing over two movies a month on average. Heavy users could burden the company with up to $50-$100, while paying just $10. The breakage model backfired as usage surged.</p> 
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
          Infrastructure and customer service collapsed under the demand. MoviePass began imposing restrictions to reduce losses, including blackout dates, surge pricing, and minimal movie choices. It even went to the lengths of resetting user logins to block high-usage profiles. This eroded trust within the very same community it had courted.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
          Ultimately, their stock tanked, and investor confidence collapsed. Service was shut down in September 2019. Founders and executives were later accused of fraud and misleading investors. The idea was irresistible, but the economics were fatal.</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Cereal entrepreneurs gone rogue </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
          Surreal, the British high-protein, low-sugar breakfast cereal brand, entered a saturated market dominated by legacy brands. Rather than competing on supermarket shelves through traditional advertising, they began <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-26-07-2025-targeting-marketers-and-advertising-professionals" target="_blank">targeting marketers and advertising professionals</a> as a core customer segment. They utilized LinkedIn as their primary social media platform to reach individuals aged 25–44. This strategic advertising pivot reshaped their trajectory. </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/surreal-creative-product-focused-content-strategy.jpg" alt="Surreal is focused on creating clever, creative product-focused content that engages people, rather than trying to be the next great reactive" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i> Surreal is focused on creating clever, creative product-focused content that engages people, rather than trying to be the next great reactive. Credits: Surreal</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          They utilized out-of-home stunt campaigns, such as humorous posters or real-world pranks, to capture attention offline, then shared those stunts on LinkedIn to go viral online. These antics generated over 500 comments on LinkedIn debating whether the campaign was genius or cringe, precisely the kind of buzz Surreal was after. </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
          With an internal creative team of just four people and outsourced video/PR, most campaigns were organic, low-production, and word-driven, yet they achieved outsized attention. Even on LinkedIn, their ads were not paid. Instead, they relied on clever copywriting and image-based carousels. </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
          
          Surreal is stocked in major retailers like Sainsbury’s, Ocado, Booths, Whole Foods Market, and Holland & Barrett, and is one of Britain’s fastest-growing independent cereal brands. Their big disruptive idea was simple: if you can’t outspend the giants, outthink them. </p>
        </mj-text>
